TY  - JOUR
AU  - Kelley, Eric K.
AU  - Tetlock, Paul C.
T1  - Retail Short Selling and Stock Prices
PY  - 2017
Y1  - 2017/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhw089
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 30
IS  - 3
SP  - 801
EP  - 834
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Using proprietary data on millions of trades by retail investors, we provide the first large-scale evidence that retail short selling predicts negative stock returns. A portfolio that mimics weekly retail shorting earns an annualized risk-adjusted return of 9%. The predictive ability of retail short selling lasts for one year and is not subsumed by institutional short selling. In contrast to institutional shorting, retail shorting best predicts returns in small stocks and those that are heavily bought by other retail investors. Our findings are consistent with retail short sellers having unique insights into the retail investor community and small firms’ fundamentals.Received May 5, 2016; editorial decision September 6, 2016 by Editor Andrew Karolyi.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhw089
ER  - 



